h3. Issue Summary
The Livesearch macro search button is not rendering properly in Confluence regardless of the size of sidebar.
In older versions like 7.6.2 the button would change it's position to the right of the sidebar if there were enough space in the sidebar. 
Instead the button is fixed below the searchbar.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Log in to Confluence.
# Choose *Space tools* > *Configure sidebar* from the bottom of the sidebar (or the cog menu if your sidebar is collapsed).
# Select *Go to space admin.*
# In the Sidebar  insert the following: 
{code}
{livesearch:spaceKey=@self|size=medium|placeholder=Search this space}
{code}
# Select *Save*.
# Try to resize the bar to check that the button does not change.

h3. Expected Results
The search button should move from the bottom of the search bar to the right side of the search bar.

h3. Actual Results
The search button is fixed below the search bar despite the size of the sidebar.

h3. Workaround
* The user can set the wiki markup of the macro to large to get the correct results: 
{code}
{livesearch:spaceKey=@self|size=large|placeholder=Search this space}
{code}

* Additionally the user can change the size of the icon to be similar to the medium size of the macro by adding the following CSS to the Stylesheet section of the space. 
{code:css}
.aui-icon-large {
    --aui-icon-size: 16px;
}
{code}

The small text in the article list needs to be two shades darker to accommodate N10 on-hover background.

You need to change N100 to N300 with something like this:
{code:java}
list-container-all-updates .update-items .update-item-date {
 color: #5E6C84;
}{code}

While creating a user macro, Confluence will overwrite the external links that are defined in the macro, such as those shown in the following example:
{code:java}
@param Text:title=Button Text|type=string|required=true
@param Link:title=External Link|type=string|desc=*Page field will override this field **Only use if page is not within Confluence
@param Color:title=Button Color|type=enum|enumValues=c-button,c-button c-button--secondary,c-button c-button--neutral,c-button c-button--neutral c-button--secondary|default=c-button--secondary|desc=Ordered: Red, Secondary Red, Blue, Secondary Blue|required=true
@param Size:title=Size|type=string|type=enum|enumValues=,c-button--small,c-button--large,c-button--jumbo|default=|desc=Leave blank for default
<a href="$paramLink" class="$paramColor $paramSize">$paramText</a>
{code}
From the macro above the following will be ignored and overwritten by Confluence:

!overwritten.png|width=650,height=175!

The goal of this suggestion is that these external links should not be overeaten so the macro creator can have more flexibility while creating or customizing the macros.

h3. Issue Summary
* The *Saved for later* page under the dashboard and the one under the user profile should show the same data, but they show different information, causing confusion and misleading information.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Click in the star icon in a Confluence page
# Navigate to both pages:
#* *Dashboard >> User profile*
#* *Profile picture >> Saved for later*

h3. Expected Results
* We should see the same results on both pages.

h3. Actual Results
* Depending on the amount of data in Confluence, the content of both pages will greatly differ.
* Here are the queries that Confluence runs when populating the *Saved for later* in the user profile page:
{code:sql}
select * from label where owner = 'userkey' and name = 'favourite';
{code}
{code:sql}
select * from content_label where labelid = id
{code}
{code:sql}
select * from content where contentid = contentid
select * from content where contentid = contentid
{code}
* Here are the queries that Confluence runs when populating the *Saved for later* in the dashboard:
{code:sql}
label0_.CREATIONDATE as CREATION5_40_0_, label0_.LASTMODDATE as LASTMODD6_40_0_ from LABEL label0_ where label0_.LABELID=$1
DETAIL:  parameters: $1 = 'labelid'
{code}
{code:sql}
LOG:  execute <unnamed>: SELECT rt.currentId as contentId, rt.draftprevver as latestVersionid, rt.RELATIONID as relationId, CASE WHEN lt.LASTMODDATE < rt.touchdate THEN rt.CONTENT_STATUS ELSE lt.CONTENT_STATUS END as contentStatus, rt.touchdate as lastModifiedDate FROM CONTENT lt JOIN ( SELECT ucr.LASTMODDATE as touchdate, ucr.RELATIONID, c.LASTMODDATE, c.CONTENTID, c.TITLE, c.CONTENT_STATUS, coalesce(c.PREVVER, c.CONTENTID) as currentId, c.PREVVER as draftprevver FROM CONTENT c LEFT JOIN USERCONTENT_RELATION ucr ON c.CONTENTID = ucr.TARGETCONTENTID WHERE ucr.RELATIONNAME = 'touched' AND ucr.LASTMODIFIER = $1     and c.CONTENTTYPE in ($2, $3)     and c.CONTENT_STATUS in ($4, $5) ) rt on lt.CONTENTID = rt.currentId WHERE lt.CONTENTID in ($6)
DETAIL:  parameters: $1 = 'userkey', $2 = 'contenttype', $3 = 'contenttype', $4 = 'status', $5 = 'status', $6 = 'contentid'
{code}

h3. Workaround
 Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available
